T1  - A community investigation from a state health department perspective: The Love Canal
A1  - Stark A.D.
Y1  - 2000//
N2  - The Love Canal landfill, a 16-acre tract, in Niagara Falls, NY contained approximately 21,800 tons of chemical wastes. Substantial migration and contamination of soil, groundwater and basement air of nearby homes became apparent in the late 1970s. Residents of the two streets adjacent to the landfill were evacuated in 1978 and residents of several nearby streets were evacuated in 1980. After extensive remediation and testing, resettlement of the area began in 1988 and was completed in 1994. The New York State Department of Health (NYSDOH) is performing a comprehensive follow-up study of approximately 6300 persons who lived near the Love Canal between 1940 and 1978. The NYSDOH has established a cohort of these persons, and has traced them and their children to determine if they are at increased risk for the development of three groups of serious health conditions. These include: (1) cause-specific mortality, (2) cancer incidence, and (3) adverse pregnancy outcomes. These endpoints were chosen based on potential exposures as estimated by location of residence, duration of residence, and calendar years of residence and the mapping of some 13,000 environmental samples that were collected in various media between 1978 and 1982. In addition, levels of Love Canal Indicator Compounds are being evaluated in 961 individual or pooled archived serum samples that were collected in 1978 by NYSDOH. The levels will be used to validate the exposure estimates and will be correlated with clinical chemistry measurements that were also made in 1978.
