T1  - Pommeranos in Brazil and a study by comet-assay for UVC induced DNA damage in fibroblasts
T3  - Pommern in Brasilien und untersuchung mit dem komet-assay auf UVC-induzierten DNA-schaden in fibroblasten
A1  - Bayerl C.
A1  - Pagung G.
A1  - Allgauer T.
A1  - Bohnert E.
A1  - Herbst C.
A1  - Fuhrmann E.
A1  - Waltering S.
Y1  - 2000//
N2  - Pommeranos in Brazil exhibit multiple non-melanoma skin cancers in young age compared to young inhabitants of a german town. Both groups were studied for DNA-damage after UVC radiation to evaluate if there might be differences in the DNA repair. In this study normal fibroblasts from patients from Germany (Rhein-Neckar-Dreieck, n = 3) with different skin types (I, II and III) were compared with normal fibroblasts from patients from Brazil (Espirito Santo, n = 3), that are german immigrants, for UVC induced DNA-damage. At different time points after UVC irradiation (5 min to 4 h, 1.8 mJ/cm2, UV Stratalinker 2400) of cultured fibroblasts repair was studied by comet-assay with gel electrophoresis after alkaline lysis. Comet shaped cells in the immunofluorescence were photodocumented, scanned and evaluated with a software program (Zero-D-Scan, Scannatycs) for the tail moment (product of % of DNA in the tail and the distance between the centers of mass of the head and the tail regions). In Pommeranos in Brazil of skin type I and II DNA damage is more exaggerated, repair starts earlier, reaches its maximum earlier but takes more time and is finished later. Pommeranos in Brazil with skin type I and II are more susceptibel to UVC induced cell damage than patients from the Rhein-Neckar-Dreieck with the same skin type. Skin type III showed no differences in both groups. Environmental high UV irradiation in Pommeranos is not the only reason for the increased occurrence of non melanoma skin cancer as the efficacy of nucleotide excision repair plays an additional role.
