T1  - Migraine and digestive comorbidity
T3  - Emicrania e comorbidita gastro-intestinale
A1  - Gabrielli M.
A1  - Gasbarrini A.
A1  - Fiore G.
A1  - Giacovazzo M.
Y1  - 2000//
N2  - Various studies have been performed in order to clarify the relations occurring between migraine and digestive diseases. The cyclic vomiting syndrome is a common functional intestinal disorder, that affects pediatric age and is often associated to migraine. Links existing between migraine and food allergies are also well known. It has been demonstrated that, in patients with evidence of positivity to skin tests for peculiar food allergens, an elimination diet is effective to significantly reduce the frequency of migraine attacks. More recently, a possible association between migraine and the gastric infection by Helicobacter pylori has been hypothesized, expecially if considering more cytotoxic CagA-positive strains of the bacterium. Eradication of this infection has been demonstrated to be followed by a signifcant decrease of frequency, duration and intensity of migraine attacks. If these preliminary findings will be confirmed, a specific antibiotic treatment could represent a novel therapeutic approach, at least for the sub-group of migraine patients infected by Helicobacter pylori.
